Let&#39;s say that we have very long routes with a lot of .split() and .multicast() and all they work in parallel, the goal is to completely stop particular inflight/exchange (not route, because all other threads will be affected). 
It doesn&#39;t matter if .onCompletion() will be executed. 
What can you recommend?

The solution that I came across with is next: 
1. Set unique id as a property at start
2. Create an http endpoint as a route which expects this id
3. Create a processor in that http route which does next:

```
      .process(exchange -&gt; {
        //id as a request body
        var id = exchange.getMessage().getBody(String.class);
        var inflightRepository = exchange.getContext().getInflightRepository();
        var exchangesToRemove = inflightRepository.browse().stream()
                               .filter(e -&gt; e.getExchange().getProperties().containsValue(id))
                               .map(InflightRepository.InflightExchange::getExchange)
                               .toList();

        exchangesToRemove.forEach(e -&gt; inflightRepository.remove(e));
      });
```
It seems to work as expected, but if we have a .split(), even though we removed parent exchange and all the exchanges that we have at the moment, split will continue create new exchanges.

